1
00:00:02,140 --> 00:00:03,140
Can we...

2
00:00:04,940 --> 00:00:08,400
start over again?

3
00:00:12,710 --> 00:00:17,000
Well... let me see.

4
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:23,760
Answer it. It's probably work.

5
00:00:24,960 --> 00:00:27,320
Oh, it's fine. I'll call them back later.

6
00:00:29,500 --> 00:00:30,530
So...

7
00:00:36,680 --> 00:00:37,700
Sorry.

8
00:00:41,260 --> 00:00:42,340
Hello?

9
00:00:43,100 --> 00:00:44,100
Yes.

10
00:00:45,340 --> 00:00:46,910
Oh, the documents?

11
00:00:47,640 --> 00:00:48,910
Please hold on a second.

12
00:00:53,980 --> 00:00:54,980
Okay.

13
00:00:55,320 --> 00:00:57,640
Oh, sorry. It looks like
they didn't go through.

14
00:00:57,820 --> 00:00:58,940
I'll resend them right away.

15
00:01:01,180 --> 00:01:02,360
Oh, not at all.

16
00:01:03,480 --> 00:01:06,800
After all, "if you can't
forgive, you don't have to."

17
00:01:09,060 --> 00:01:11,130
Okay, talk to you later.

18
00:01:11,930 --> 00:01:12,930
Goodbye.

19
00:01:17,680 --> 00:01:19,310
Sorry, that was Kubota-san.

20
00:01:19,680 --> 00:01:21,399
You remember him, right?
The one I introduced to you at the bar.

21
00:01:21,400 --> 00:01:22,800
What did you mean by that just now?

22
00:01:23,520 --> 00:01:24,520
Huh?

23
00:01:25,380 --> 00:01:28,880
That line,
"if you can't forgive, you don't have to."

24
00:01:29,420 --> 00:01:30,420
Oh, that.

25
00:01:31,380 --> 00:01:34,200
We happened to talk
about it after today's shoot.

26
00:01:35,160 --> 00:01:36,400
It's a great quote, isn't it?

27
00:01:36,890 --> 00:01:38,590
Kayano-san really related to it too.

28
00:01:42,520 --> 00:01:44,600
Isn't there a term called
"microaggression"?

29
00:01:44,940 --> 00:01:46,460
It's those subtle, unconscious biases.

30
00:01:47,100 --> 00:01:49,620
Like, "Since you're gay, you
must understand women's feelings."

31
00:01:50,460 --> 00:01:51,779
Even though we've quietly
put up with it until now...

32
00:01:51,780 --> 00:01:53,300
If you feel like you can forgive them,

33
00:01:56,280 --> 00:01:58,286
then there's nothing wrong
with choosing to forgive, right?

34
00:01:58,310 --> 00:01:59,310
Huh?

35
00:01:59,780 --> 00:02:02,649
How you treat someone who
steps on your foot on purpose

36
00:02:02,650 --> 00:02:04,650
is different from someone
who does it by accident.

37
00:02:05,760 --> 00:02:07,620
If you feel like it's no big deal,

38
00:02:08,420 --> 00:02:10,030
choosing to forgive is always an option.

39
00:02:13,920 --> 00:02:18,580
I think forgiving someone is actually
harder than not forgiving them.

40
00:02:20,600 --> 00:02:24,740
But don't you forgive people too easily?

41
00:02:30,103 --> 00:02:31,103
What?

42
00:02:33,020 --> 00:02:36,280
You were forced to resign
and didn't even fight back.

43
00:02:36,560 --> 00:02:37,819
That wasn't because it
was too much trouble.

44
00:02:37,820 --> 00:02:39,820
You were actually just
holding it in, weren't you?

45
00:02:40,540 --> 00:02:42,320
You're always the only one holding back.

46
00:02:42,800 --> 00:02:44,720
That's just wrong, no
matter how you look at it.

47
00:02:50,300 --> 00:02:51,300
Then what if...

48
00:02:54,561 --> 00:02:58,241
Say I messed up this
dish and it tasted terrible.

49
00:02:59,560 --> 00:03:00,560
Yeah.

50
00:03:01,197 --> 00:03:06,256
And you told a depressed me,
"Everyone makes mistakes."

51
00:03:06,280 --> 00:03:07,480
To comfort me like that.

52
00:03:07,500 --> 00:03:08,980
That would be considered kind, right?

53
00:03:09,880 --> 00:03:10,880
Yeah...

54
00:03:11,540 --> 00:03:15,360
But what if I thought it tasted
great and was happy with it,

55
00:03:16,520 --> 00:03:18,329
yet because it didn't suit your taste,

56
00:03:18,330 --> 00:03:20,160
you decided I failed,

57
00:03:21,020 --> 00:03:24,300
and told me, "Everyone makes mistakes"?

58
00:03:24,600 --> 00:03:26,520
Do you still think that's being kind?

59
00:03:32,760 --> 00:03:34,280
That's your problem.

60
00:03:40,720 --> 00:03:44,020
I'll just pretend I didn't
hear what you said earlier.

61
00:03:53,830 --> 00:03:56,300
- We're back. Good work today.
- You startled me!

62
00:03:56,870 --> 00:03:57,430
Huh?

63
00:03:57,431 --> 00:03:59,059
Were you filming today too?

64
00:03:59,060 --> 00:04:00,799
- Yes.
- How did it go?

65
00:04:00,800 --> 00:04:03,369
Well, Kasuga-san was very cooperative.

66
00:04:03,370 --> 00:04:05,370
We got a lot of natural footage.

67
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:08,480
But Hasegawa-san still seemed very guarded.

68
00:04:08,680 --> 00:04:10,440
I feel like we didn't
get any good material.

69
00:04:10,480 --> 00:04:11,480
Oh, I see.

70
00:04:11,510 --> 00:04:12,580
Is that so?

71
00:04:13,000 --> 00:04:13,870
Actually,

72
00:04:13,871 --> 00:04:15,599
I think Itsuki-san seemed more natural.

73
00:04:15,600 --> 00:04:17,109
Like today, even though
the camera was rolling,

74
00:04:17,110 --> 00:04:18,750
he was just playing games the whole time.

75
00:04:19,020 --> 00:04:20,466
We can't use footage like that at all.

76
00:04:20,490 --> 00:04:21,490
What?

77
00:04:22,590 --> 00:04:24,729
- Check your LINE.
- LINE?

78
00:04:24,730 --> 00:04:25,730
Look.

79
00:04:30,500 --> 00:04:32,230
Naomi-san had her baby!

80
00:04:33,800 --> 00:04:35,270
So cute!

81
00:04:40,440 --> 00:04:41,540
There are eggs!

82
00:04:42,740 --> 00:04:43,950
(Day 21)
Wow...

83
00:04:44,410 --> 00:04:45,410
Hmm?

84
00:04:45,780 --> 00:04:46,850
Ah...

85
00:04:51,040 --> 00:04:52,099
What's wrong?

86
00:04:52,100 --> 00:04:54,360
Nothing, I just turned on
the dryer before going to bed.

87
00:04:54,790 --> 00:04:55,990
But they're still soaking wet.

88
00:04:57,820 --> 00:04:59,880
Ah, this machine is a goner.

89
00:04:59,940 --> 00:05:01,040
It's broken.

90
00:05:01,960 --> 00:05:03,340
What should I do?

91
00:05:04,080 --> 00:05:05,080
Huh?

92
00:05:05,520 --> 00:05:07,940
I mean, I have nothing to
wear for the shoot today.

93
00:05:08,500 --> 00:05:09,500
Oh...

94
00:05:11,270 --> 00:05:13,080
Do you want to wear mine?

95
00:05:13,460 --> 00:05:14,480
Yours?

96
00:05:15,240 --> 00:05:16,639
No way, they won't suit me.

97
00:05:16,640 --> 00:05:17,980
What do you mean, "no way"?

98
00:05:18,010 --> 00:05:20,480
But you'll be late if you don't leave now.

99
00:05:22,950 --> 00:05:24,990
Am I really wearing yours...?

100
00:05:25,290 --> 00:05:26,820
Why do you look so disgusted?

101
00:06:04,900 --> 00:06:11,900
"The Boy and I Who Will Break Up in 100 Days"
(Episode 3)

102
00:06:15,840 --> 00:06:16,410
Hasegawa-san,

103
00:06:16,440 --> 00:06:19,270
you look a bit different than usual today.

104
00:06:19,740 --> 00:06:20,740
Oh.

105
00:06:20,830 --> 00:06:21,590
Huh?
Really?

106
00:06:22,231 --> 00:06:24,670
Yes, today's outfit
suits you very well too.

107
00:06:24,950 --> 00:06:27,350
Yeah, it really suits you.

108
00:06:33,040 --> 00:06:34,040
Thank you both.

109
00:06:35,410 --> 00:06:36,410
Yuma.

110
00:06:37,270 --> 00:06:38,730
Oh, Katagiri-san.

111
00:06:39,090 --> 00:06:41,560
Yuma, can I introduce you
to the kids from the club?

112
00:06:42,250 --> 00:06:43,270
Of course.

113
00:06:48,030 --> 00:06:49,230
This is Yuma-senpai.

114
00:06:50,390 --> 00:06:51,390
Nice to meet you.

115
00:06:55,030 --> 00:06:59,010
Hasegawa-san, didn't you join
this kind of club in college?

116
00:07:01,050 --> 00:07:02,450
I didn't go to college.

117
00:07:03,320 --> 00:07:05,290
Oh, I see.

118
00:07:05,910 --> 00:07:06,910
Is that so?

119
00:07:07,850 --> 00:07:08,859
Well...

120
00:07:08,860 --> 00:07:10,330
I didn't go to college either.

121
00:07:11,130 --> 00:07:12,130
Oh?

122
00:07:12,710 --> 00:07:16,010
But you're about the same
age as those students, right?

123
00:07:16,230 --> 00:07:17,270
That's true.

124
00:07:18,130 --> 00:07:19,530
Maybe I'm even younger than them.

125
00:07:21,990 --> 00:07:23,550
That's impressive for someone so young.

126
00:07:24,210 --> 00:07:26,170
Unlike me, who doesn't
even have a job right now.

127
00:07:26,540 --> 00:07:28,010
Then why don't you just get a job?

128
00:07:29,670 --> 00:07:31,510
I work really hard on my game, though.

129
00:07:31,710 --> 00:07:33,320
I'm constantly developing cities.

130
00:07:33,470 --> 00:07:34,220
Huh?
Which game is it?

131
00:07:36,830 --> 00:07:38,750
Oh, that one shut down
its servers long ago.

132
00:07:38,890 --> 00:07:41,390
Wow, jobless even in a game.

133
00:07:42,890 --> 00:07:44,590
- Cool, right?
- Super cool.

134
00:07:46,210 --> 00:07:48,290
- It's cold. I'm going to the restroom.
- Sure thing.

135
00:07:51,970 --> 00:07:53,170
You're getting close quickly.

136
00:07:53,470 --> 00:07:55,176
Right? I think so too.

137
00:07:55,200 --> 00:07:57,189
Oh, if you don't have enough
footage of Hasegawa-san,

138
00:07:57,190 --> 00:07:58,270
should I interview him?

139
00:07:58,310 --> 00:07:59,070
Compared to Shiho-san,

140
00:07:59,110 --> 00:08:00,416
he'd probably feel more
comfortable talking to me.

141
00:08:00,440 --> 00:08:01,480
That's not what I meant.

142
00:08:01,580 --> 00:08:03,020
I mean you're being too thoughtless.

143
00:08:03,950 --> 00:08:06,750
Hasegawa-san lost his job
because of discrimination,

144
00:08:07,430 --> 00:08:09,696
yet you casually say things like
"just get a job" and "jobless" to him.

145
00:08:09,720 --> 00:08:11,590
That's not something you should joke about.

146
00:08:12,970 --> 00:08:14,590
Because we are the majority.

147
00:08:16,930 --> 00:08:18,930
I think that's probably
where the problem lies.

148
00:08:20,790 --> 00:08:21,800
Huh?

149
00:08:28,350 --> 00:08:29,850
I realized it pretty late.

150
00:08:30,450 --> 00:08:33,680
Maybe around my
freshman year of high school?

151
00:08:34,250 --> 00:08:39,350
There was a girl three years older than me
at my part-time job.

152
00:08:39,850 --> 00:08:44,850
I realized I had feelings for her.

153
00:08:45,090 --> 00:08:49,760
My heart would race
every time I went to work.

154
00:08:50,450 --> 00:08:54,090
Even though I could tell
the friends around me,

155
00:08:54,590 --> 00:08:57,450
she was the only one I
couldn't bring myself to tell.

156
00:08:58,630 --> 00:09:01,470
I guess that was my first love.

157
00:09:03,230 --> 00:09:05,270
There's even fan art of you guys online.

158
00:09:05,430 --> 00:09:06,530
Like this one.

159
00:09:07,390 --> 00:09:09,330
And this one too.

160
00:09:11,070 --> 00:09:12,379
This is really... how should I put it...

161
00:09:12,380 --> 00:09:13,766
They made us look way too handsome.

162
00:09:13,790 --> 00:09:15,070
No, no, no, no.

163
00:09:15,090 --> 00:09:18,030
Now that I've met you in person, I
think you're even more handsome.

164
00:09:18,090 --> 00:09:18,690
Right?

165
00:09:18,719 --> 00:09:20,595
We're not celebrities.

166
00:09:20,620 --> 00:09:23,030
By the way, please don't forget to sign.

167
00:09:23,830 --> 00:09:24,820
Can I take a picture?
Please sign for me too.

168
00:09:25,691 --> 00:09:26,730
Please.

169
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:28,060
Kasuga-san.

170
00:09:28,330 --> 00:09:29,400
Oh.

171
00:09:31,546 --> 00:09:33,999
Do you remember Mori Naomi? She was
the one in charge of this project before.

172
00:09:34,040 --> 00:09:35,300
Oh, of course I do.

173
00:09:35,670 --> 00:09:38,670
Her passion for this documentary
really left an impression on me.

174
00:09:39,410 --> 00:09:40,410
Oh.

175
00:09:40,450 --> 00:09:41,930
- Don't tell me...
- Yes.

176
00:09:43,330 --> 00:09:45,160
- Congratulations to her.
- Thank you.

177
00:09:45,450 --> 00:09:47,880
And, if you don't mind,

178
00:09:47,920 --> 00:09:49,369
I thought we could celebrate

179
00:09:49,370 --> 00:09:50,869
by going to visit her together.

180
00:09:50,870 --> 00:09:52,270
It suits you very well.

181
00:09:53,120 --> 00:09:54,590
Oh, this isn't my outfit.

182
00:09:54,760 --> 00:09:56,830
Huh?! What do you mean?

183
00:09:56,860 --> 00:09:57,890
Is this Kasuga-senpai's?

184
00:09:57,930 --> 00:09:58,930
Oh, yes.

185
00:10:00,030 --> 00:10:01,566
He said the clothes he's wearing
today belong to Kasuga-senpai.

186
00:10:01,590 --> 00:10:04,649
I'm so jealous that
couples can share clothes.

187
00:10:04,650 --> 00:10:06,630
Oh, no, it's not really sharing.

188
00:10:08,470 --> 00:10:11,010
Actually, it doesn't look that bad.

189
00:10:13,990 --> 00:10:15,349
Hey, how did you feel about today?

190
00:10:15,350 --> 00:10:16,550
Hmm? About what?

191
00:10:17,550 --> 00:10:18,750
After listening to the talk

192
00:10:19,170 --> 00:10:20,679
and chatting with those young people.

193
00:10:20,680 --> 00:10:22,450
Didn't you feel anything?

194
00:10:23,390 --> 00:10:24,670
No, nothing in particular.

195
00:10:26,750 --> 00:10:27,750
Before,

196
00:10:28,310 --> 00:10:29,890
didn't I ask you to tell a lie

197
00:10:29,930 --> 00:10:32,050
for the sake of the documentary?

198
00:10:32,630 --> 00:10:33,630
Yeah.

199
00:10:34,509 --> 00:10:36,809
Those kids I saw today are my answer.

200
00:10:38,610 --> 00:10:40,019
On our shoulders,

201
00:10:40,020 --> 00:10:42,230
we carry the lives of those children.

202
00:10:43,410 --> 00:10:45,530
It's not a matter of whether
we want to do it or not.

203
00:10:46,070 --> 00:10:47,550
It just naturally became our reality.

204
00:10:49,010 --> 00:10:51,430
I don't want to let those kids down.

205
00:10:53,250 --> 00:10:57,050
I hope that when those kids
reach our age,

206
00:10:58,310 --> 00:11:02,550
they can live in a kinder world than this.

207
00:11:04,050 --> 00:11:05,850
You feel the same way
about this, don't you?

208
00:11:08,490 --> 00:11:09,590
You know...

209
00:11:10,490 --> 00:11:11,490
Yeah?

210
00:11:11,750 --> 00:11:16,000
Are you going to spend your
whole life living for others?

211
00:11:17,240 --> 00:11:18,400
I certainly wouldn't want to.

212
00:11:24,580 --> 00:11:25,780
By the way,

213
00:11:26,650 --> 00:11:28,970
it seems like you're always
walking ahead, and I'm behind.

214
00:11:29,730 --> 00:11:30,730
Really?

215
00:11:31,150 --> 00:11:32,150
Yeah.

216
00:11:33,530 --> 00:11:34,960
No way, that's not true.

217
00:11:35,590 --> 00:11:37,530
Before I know it, you're
always ahead of me.

218
00:11:38,260 --> 00:11:39,260
I am not.

219
00:11:39,550 --> 00:11:40,870
Yes, you are.

220
00:11:45,010 --> 00:11:48,589
That's why I wanted to start a
group that values differences.

221
00:11:48,590 --> 00:11:51,809
That's why I founded Marginal Women.

222
00:11:51,810 --> 00:11:55,589
Do you remember the first time
you fell for a girl?

223
00:11:55,590 --> 00:11:57,030
I realized it pretty late.

224
00:12:16,500 --> 00:12:17,600
Well...

225
00:12:17,659 --> 00:12:21,379
I really look up to women like her.

226
00:12:21,980 --> 00:12:24,310
Someone who has clear ideas of her own

227
00:12:24,480 --> 00:12:26,040
and actually puts them into action.

228
00:12:28,240 --> 00:12:33,750
But at the same time, I couldn't help
comparing myself to her...

229
00:12:35,200 --> 00:12:36,819
Just like this project.

230
00:12:36,820 --> 00:12:39,990
Naomi-san was originally
supposed to be in charge of it.

231
00:12:43,060 --> 00:12:44,060
Yeah...

232
00:12:44,100 --> 00:12:48,000
Naomi-san is a mentor I really admire, too.

233
00:12:48,940 --> 00:12:50,699
Once, when I was feeling really down,

234
00:12:50,700 --> 00:12:52,570
no one else noticed,

235
00:12:52,600 --> 00:12:54,500
but she did.

236
00:12:56,440 --> 00:13:00,760
The strength that she possess...

237
00:13:02,300 --> 00:13:06,060
her kindness, and her empathy...

238
00:13:07,080 --> 00:13:12,080
I admire everything about her.

239
00:13:14,380 --> 00:13:16,260
You're asking what kind
of film I want to make?

240
00:13:17,320 --> 00:13:19,560
Well,

241
00:13:21,460 --> 00:13:29,460
I want to capture the most authentic sides
of Kasuga-san and Hasegawa-san.

242
00:13:33,080 --> 00:13:34,080
Yeah...

243
00:13:42,820 --> 00:13:44,200
What on earth am I doing?

244
00:13:45,800 --> 00:13:46,730
What am I even doing?
Seriously.

245
00:13:48,020 --> 00:13:49,660
I don't know what's wrong with me.

246
00:13:52,000 --> 00:13:56,000
(The 40th APVOD Awards
Best Newcomer: Mori Naomi)

247
00:13:56,940 --> 00:13:58,600
Oh.

248
00:13:58,920 --> 00:14:01,939
So this is how you meet like-minded people.

249
00:14:01,940 --> 00:14:03,840
Yeah, pretty much.

250
00:14:04,780 --> 00:14:06,880
Is that how you two met?

251
00:14:07,580 --> 00:14:08,580
Yeah.

252
00:14:09,080 --> 00:14:10,080
Who made the first move?

253
00:14:10,710 --> 00:14:11,500
Huh?

254
00:14:11,501 --> 00:14:12,700
He messaged me first.

255
00:14:13,960 --> 00:14:15,880
Do you get a lot of messages like that?

256
00:14:16,600 --> 00:14:18,750
If you're curious, President,
you should try it too.

257
00:14:19,820 --> 00:14:21,260
I'm only into women.

258
00:14:21,284 --> 00:14:22,336
(Day 42)

259
00:14:22,360 --> 00:14:24,120
But maybe I'll actually
download it one day.

260
00:14:24,680 --> 00:14:26,640
What if I match with some
creepy old guy, though?

261
00:14:28,940 --> 00:14:31,519
Ah, welcome.

262
00:14:31,520 --> 00:14:34,420
- I tagged along too.
- You cut your hair.

263
00:14:34,480 --> 00:14:36,070
- It really suits you.
- Thanks.

264
00:14:37,040 --> 00:14:38,739
Please, come in.

265
00:14:38,740 --> 00:14:40,079
- Thanks for having us.
- Excuse us.

266
00:14:40,080 --> 00:14:43,650
- Excuse us.
- Excuse us.

267
00:14:47,340 --> 00:14:49,700
Make yourselves at home, everyone.

268
00:14:51,340 --> 00:14:53,519
Ah, Naomi-san, let me help.

269
00:14:53,520 --> 00:14:56,160
It's fine. I should move
around a bit more anyway.

270
00:14:56,190 --> 00:14:57,020
Ah.

271
00:14:57,060 --> 00:14:59,460
Naomi, here's a gift from the catalog.

272
00:14:59,880 --> 00:15:00,999
No need to get me anything in return.

273
00:15:01,000 --> 00:15:02,820
Thank you.

274
00:15:02,860 --> 00:15:05,239
I'll do my best to get back
to work as soon as possible.

275
00:15:05,240 --> 00:15:06,240
No, no, don't rush.

276
00:15:06,300 --> 00:15:08,816
Isn't your husband an executive producer
for that variety show at the TV station?

277
00:15:08,840 --> 00:15:11,819
Take your full maternity
and childcare leave.

278
00:15:11,820 --> 00:15:13,100
Just get some good rest at home.

279
00:15:13,520 --> 00:15:16,480
Shiho will work hard to cover for you.

280
00:15:17,320 --> 00:15:18,320
I'll do my best.

281
00:15:20,800 --> 00:15:21,800
Ah.

282
00:15:22,620 --> 00:15:24,649
Naomi-san, here's a little something,
if you don't mind.

283
00:15:24,650 --> 00:15:25,570
Oh?

284
00:15:25,571 --> 00:15:27,060
I bought some baby bibs.

285
00:15:27,090 --> 00:15:28,560
Wow, thank you!

286
00:15:31,980 --> 00:15:33,000
So cute.

287
00:15:34,440 --> 00:15:35,880
Do you want to try holding him?

288
00:15:35,900 --> 00:15:36,900
Huh?

289
00:15:37,040 --> 00:15:38,360
- Really? Is it okay?
- Of course.

290
00:15:39,280 --> 00:15:41,346
His neck isn't fully stable
yet, so support it carefully.

291
00:15:41,370 --> 00:15:42,600
Yes, just like that.

292
00:15:45,870 --> 00:15:47,210
Ah, you're a natural.

293
00:15:50,280 --> 00:15:51,356
Make sure you don't break him.

294
00:15:51,380 --> 00:15:53,780
Hey, don't say such scary things!

295
00:15:55,620 --> 00:15:56,719
Hasegawa-san, Hasegawa-san.

296
00:15:56,720 --> 00:15:58,750
Come over and help make the baby smile.

297
00:15:59,320 --> 00:16:00,080
Me?
Yeah.

298
00:16:01,520 --> 00:16:02,520
How do I do that?
Huh?

299
00:16:03,790 --> 00:16:04,890
Like, making a funny face?

300
00:16:05,060 --> 00:16:06,060
A funny face?

301
00:16:06,460 --> 00:16:08,660
- Give it a try.
- I've actually never seen you do that.

302
00:16:16,180 --> 00:16:17,640
It's funny, right?

303
00:16:17,740 --> 00:16:18,799
That's hilarious.

304
00:16:18,800 --> 00:16:20,110
We woke the baby up.

305
00:16:26,120 --> 00:16:28,350
- Do you always wear it like this?
- Yeah.

306
00:16:32,440 --> 00:16:34,840
- By the way, Shiho.
- Yes?

307
00:16:35,840 --> 00:16:39,440
Yamada and I will take
these two back today.

308
00:16:40,700 --> 00:16:42,400
You should stay here with Naomi.

309
00:16:43,540 --> 00:16:44,540
Huh?

310
00:16:44,980 --> 00:16:48,660
You haven't seen each other in a while. I'm sure
you have plenty of girl talk to catch up on.

311
00:16:48,740 --> 00:16:49,740
Right, Naomi?

312
00:16:50,860 --> 00:16:53,759
I'm absolutely dying for some
adult conversation right now.

313
00:16:53,760 --> 00:16:55,279
I knew it.

314
00:16:55,280 --> 00:16:59,550
Enjoy some long-overdue
girl talk about love.

315
00:17:00,760 --> 00:17:01,950
Thank you.

316
00:17:03,120 --> 00:17:04,120
Alright.

317
00:17:05,960 --> 00:17:07,160
We'll head out now.

318
00:17:07,390 --> 00:17:08,320
Thanks for having us today.

319
00:17:08,360 --> 00:17:09,459
- Thanks for the hospitality.
- Get home safe.

320
00:17:09,460 --> 00:17:10,200
See you next time.

321
00:17:10,201 --> 00:17:12,159
- Okay, thank you so much today.
- Keep up the good work.

322
00:17:12,160 --> 00:17:13,576
- Okay, get home safe.
- Thanks for today.

323
00:17:13,600 --> 00:17:15,700
- Thank you.
- Thank you, everyone.

324
00:17:22,220 --> 00:17:24,646
I'm so sorry... I can't believe
the president tagged along too.

325
00:17:24,670 --> 00:17:26,499
Was he that annoying?

326
00:17:26,500 --> 00:17:27,799
How could he say things like that?

327
00:17:27,800 --> 00:17:28,939
To tell an employee on childcare leave,

328
00:17:28,940 --> 00:17:32,050
"A lot of men cheat during
this time, so watch out."

329
00:17:32,120 --> 00:17:34,780
But I know he forced his way here.

330
00:17:34,880 --> 00:17:37,250
And there's no way you
could've stopped him.

331
00:17:40,280 --> 00:17:41,280
Hey,

332
00:17:41,440 --> 00:17:43,530
do you two have any plans after this?

333
00:17:43,660 --> 00:17:46,599
After this? Nothing in particular.

334
00:17:46,600 --> 00:17:47,400
Ah, perfect.

335
00:17:47,401 --> 00:17:50,870
Why don't you go grab
a drink with our Yamada?

336
00:17:51,000 --> 00:17:51,630
Huh?

337
00:17:51,631 --> 00:17:54,200
You'll be working together
for quite a while, right?

338
00:17:54,340 --> 00:17:55,900
It'd be good to get to know each other.

339
00:17:56,860 --> 00:17:58,939
I'll pitch in 10,000 yen.

340
00:17:58,940 --> 00:17:59,540
Wait, really?
Oh!

341
00:18:00,541 --> 00:18:03,550
- I'll drive the car back.
- Okay.

342
00:18:03,800 --> 00:18:05,020
I'll leave this to you then.

343
00:18:06,040 --> 00:18:07,040
Seriously?

344
00:18:07,460 --> 00:18:08,460
Thank you!

345
00:18:08,620 --> 00:18:09,620
Awesome.

346
00:18:12,720 --> 00:18:15,660
- Also, do you remember Katagiri-san?
- Yeah...

347
00:18:15,680 --> 00:18:17,980
She said she hates Girls' Day.

348
00:18:18,570 --> 00:18:20,489
She feels like it arbitrarily
defines a woman's happiness,

349
00:18:20,490 --> 00:18:21,690
which makes her uncomfortable.

350
00:18:22,060 --> 00:18:24,099
I think if someone like her is
willing to help with the shoot,

351
00:18:24,100 --> 00:18:25,516
we can make the kind of
documentary Naomi-san talked about??

352
00:18:25,540 --> 00:18:30,370
one that breaks down gender biases.

353
00:18:32,550 --> 00:18:34,509
You're doing a really great job.

354
00:18:34,510 --> 00:18:35,510
Yes.

355
00:18:35,810 --> 00:18:37,579
I'll work hard for your
sake too, Naomi-san.

356
00:18:37,580 --> 00:18:39,520
Please just focus on resting.

357
00:18:42,750 --> 00:18:43,890
Ah.

358
00:18:50,770 --> 00:18:51,860
Naomi-san?

359
00:18:55,390 --> 00:18:58,070
If you're working hard
for my sake too, Shiho...

360
00:18:58,500 --> 00:19:00,670
does that mean I'm not needed anymore?

361
00:19:02,970 --> 00:19:04,540
What are you talking about?

362
00:19:07,550 --> 00:19:08,550
You know,

363
00:19:10,390 --> 00:19:13,830
since I got out of the hospital, I haven't
been able to turn on the TV for a long time.

364
00:19:15,850 --> 00:19:17,790
I feel like while I'm resting,

365
00:19:18,750 --> 00:19:21,560
the world is slowly
taking away my place in it.

366
00:19:24,830 --> 00:19:27,030
Every time people tell me to rest,

367
00:19:28,710 --> 00:19:32,210
I feel like I'm being locked
inside a tiny box.

368
00:19:34,130 --> 00:19:37,370
My husband, who's in the same
industry, gets to keep working.

369
00:19:38,230 --> 00:19:41,540
So why is it that only I have to stop
and rest? I really don't understand.

370
00:19:49,180 --> 00:19:51,250
Is it okay if you don't check on the baby?

371
00:19:54,520 --> 00:19:55,790
Actually...

372
00:19:57,970 --> 00:20:01,530
I've been secretly hoping
your project would fail.

373
00:20:05,450 --> 00:20:07,770
The moment you saw me,
you pointed out my haircut.

374
00:20:09,190 --> 00:20:12,270
I couldn't stand it from that very second.

375
00:20:14,330 --> 00:20:16,589
It's not like I wanted to cut it.

376
00:20:16,590 --> 00:20:19,010
I just didn't have the
energy to manage long hair.

377
00:20:19,080 --> 00:20:21,220
And I've been so frustrated about it.

378
00:20:22,210 --> 00:20:24,010
I know I'm taking it out on you,

379
00:20:24,090 --> 00:20:26,090
but I can't stop myself.

380
00:20:27,190 --> 00:20:32,230
Please, just get out of my sight.

381
00:20:33,130 --> 00:20:36,470
Even at this very moment,
that's all I can think.

382
00:20:40,070 --> 00:20:41,870
Tell me... what on earth
am I supposed to do?

383
00:21:13,500 --> 00:21:16,570
So, Kasuga-san, you do want kids, right?

384
00:21:16,930 --> 00:21:19,240
Why is that? Give me a straight answer.

385
00:21:19,270 --> 00:21:21,080
What's with that tone?

386
00:21:21,580 --> 00:21:23,350
Because I want to be a director too.

387
00:21:23,750 --> 00:21:24,810
Oh?

388
00:21:24,920 --> 00:21:25,969
So you don't want to
be a cameraman forever.

389
00:21:25,970 --> 00:21:26,970
Yeah.

390
00:21:27,320 --> 00:21:28,519
Right now, because of budget cuts,

391
00:21:28,520 --> 00:21:30,480
I'm pulling double duty
as an assistant director.

392
00:21:32,810 --> 00:21:33,490
What about you?

393
00:21:33,560 --> 00:21:34,960
Don't you want kids in the future?

394
00:21:35,990 --> 00:21:38,660
Well... I feel like I'll
probably want them someday.

395
00:21:39,650 --> 00:21:40,890
Then isn't that the same thing?

396
00:21:41,830 --> 00:21:42,929
Many people probably
think that since we're gay,

397
00:21:42,930 --> 00:21:45,470
wanting a child is an unrealistic dream.

398
00:21:46,350 --> 00:21:48,190
But when you want
something, you just want it.

399
00:21:49,940 --> 00:21:51,510
I don't feel the need for that at all.

400
00:21:53,470 --> 00:21:56,710
I don't think a child
would be happy with me.

401
00:21:57,480 --> 00:21:59,050
I always put myself first,

402
00:21:59,730 --> 00:22:01,320
and I live day to day.

403
00:22:03,650 --> 00:22:05,050
Besides, I'm gay.

404
00:22:06,550 --> 00:22:09,960
Being gay doesn't mean
you can't make a child happy.

405
00:22:10,030 --> 00:22:11,729
But it definitely makes things harder.

406
00:22:11,730 --> 00:22:13,650
That's the fault of the
people making it harder.

407
00:22:14,130 --> 00:22:15,000
If someone told a heterosexual couple,

408
00:22:15,001 --> 00:22:16,929
"Your child won't be happy,

409
00:22:16,930 --> 00:22:17,550
so don't have one,"

410
00:22:17,551 --> 00:22:19,911
there would be something
wrong with the person saying that.

411
00:22:21,550 --> 00:22:23,440
It's the same for gay people.

412
00:22:24,640 --> 00:22:28,409
It's wrong to deny gay people the right
to have children just because of prejudice.

413
00:22:28,410 --> 00:22:30,749
I'm not talking about rights.
I'm talking about commitment.

414
00:22:30,750 --> 00:22:31,610
Huh?

415
00:22:31,611 --> 00:22:33,349
Oh, um... Maybe I should
order a "Commitment Highball."

416
00:22:33,350 --> 00:22:35,220
Then why not just make that commitment?

417
00:22:36,450 --> 00:22:38,519
Even if you think you're
talking about commitment,

418
00:22:38,520 --> 00:22:41,320
society will twist your words
into a debate about rights at any moment.

419
00:22:42,350 --> 00:22:44,690
It's about time you understood that.

420
00:22:48,370 --> 00:22:49,830
I do understand.

421
00:22:52,190 --> 00:22:54,270
That's why I didn't say
it in front of the camera.

422
00:23:01,740 --> 00:23:02,780
Excuse me...

423
00:23:03,370 --> 00:23:04,949
I'm sorry. I asked a weird question.

424
00:23:04,950 --> 00:23:06,980
It's all my fault.

425
00:23:08,010 --> 00:23:09,550
So please don't fight.

426
00:23:10,710 --> 00:23:12,199
If I ruined your relationship

427
00:23:12,200 --> 00:23:14,320
and we can't go on with the shoot,

428
00:23:14,990 --> 00:23:16,490
I won't be able to live with myself.

429
00:23:20,530 --> 00:23:21,690
Yamada,

430
00:23:22,700 --> 00:23:23,700
do you live alone?

431
00:23:24,830 --> 00:23:25,500
Huh?

432
00:23:25,570 --> 00:23:27,490
Yes, I live by myself.

433
00:23:29,370 --> 00:23:30,370
I see.

434
00:23:30,610 --> 00:23:31,640
In that case...

435
00:23:34,280 --> 00:23:35,640
let me stay at your place tonight.

436
00:23:37,810 --> 00:23:38,810
What?

437
00:23:42,520 --> 00:23:43,520
Huh?

438
00:23:45,370 --> 00:23:47,626
[Next Episode] So Hasegawa-san
is staying at Yamada's place?

439
00:23:47,650 --> 00:23:49,630
Itsuki just insisted on
staying at his place.

440
00:23:51,290 --> 00:23:52,330
He moves fast, doesn't he?

441
00:23:52,570 --> 00:23:53,770
What is going on?

442
00:23:53,850 --> 00:23:57,629
We were never a lovey-dovey
couple to begin with.

443
00:23:57,630 --> 00:23:59,900
I hate myself for this.
